One undamaged fruiting body of
R. nobilis
was extracted with CH 2 Cl 2 for 10 min. After solvent removal, the 1 H NMR spectrum of the residue corresponded to that of velutinal stearate 1 (
), contaminated by low-intensity signals of unsaturated fatty acid esters. The residue was exposed to 1 mM NaOEt in EtOH at 22 °C overnight. After EtOH removal, the residue was suspended in Et 2 O and rapidly filtered though a short pad of silica gel to give (+)-velutinal 2 , identical with the literature (
) and a mixture of ethyl esters. Ethyl stearate (73%), oleate (9.5%), linoleate (7.5%), and palmitate (7%) were identified by GC –MS analysis, along with other (less than 1% each) unidentified fatty acid ethyl esters.

